Fragility of a Flat World
The world is flat!
Columnist Thomas Friedman put it this way. Friedman chose this provocative title for his bestseller to draw attention to the astonishing impact of technology on the world economy.
Distances are shrinking.
Geographical barriers can no longer provide assurance easily.
Manufacturing workers in Europe and the United States and high-tech professionals must all face the challenge of global competition.
When Western consumers call local companies, the employees they speak with may well be in India.
Skeptics pointed out the limitations of Friedman's metaphor.
As some have said, the world is not flat but "uneven."
The contour lines of the world economy show prosperous peaks and impoverished valleys.
Moreover, distances still matter.
Even neighboring countries with relatively low tariff barriers, such as Canada and the United States, engage in much more domestic trade than cross-border trade.
Seattle and Vancouver are geographically close, but trade between Vancouver and the farther Toronto is much higher than that with nearby Seattle.
Despite such criticisms, Friedman still made an important point.
Globalization can be defined as interdependence among different continents, a history as long as that of humanity, witnessing the migration of races and religions, as well as trade along the ancient Silk Roads between medieval Europe and Asia.
But today's globalization is different, developing at a faster pace and to a greater extent.
After the first transatlantic cable was laid in 1868, Europe and the United States could communicate with each other within just one minute.
In 1919, economist John Maynard Keynes envisioned a Londoner placing orders for goods from around the world via telephone and then waiting at home for delivery in the afternoon.
But Keynes's British citizen was an exception, wealthy beyond most.
Today, people worldwide can purchase goods from all over the world at local supermarkets.
Similarly, there was real-time global communication two decades ago, but it exceeded the economic means of most people.
Now, almost anyone can step into a internet cafe to gain capabilities once restricted to governments, multinational corporations, and a few individuals or institutions with substantial budgets.
The significant reduction in computing, communication, and transportation costs has made technology more accessible.
Just ten years ago, two-thirds of internet users were concentrated in the United States.
And today, the proportion of internet users in the United States accounts for less than a quarter of the global user base.
Knowledge is power, and today, the number of people who possess information has reached the highest level in human history.
Non-governmental organizations now possess capabilities that were previously restricted to governments.
National states remain the primary actors in world politics for now, but they must learn to share the vast stage with more participants, including institutions like Oxfam, celebrities like Bono, and transnational terrorist networks like al-Qaeda.
But this flattening process is reversible.
Similar situations have occurred before.
The world economy was highly integrated in 1914, but economic interdependence among nations declined over the subsequent three decades.
By 1970, the global economy had recovered to the level of integration it had previously achieved, although it was still heavily constrained by the Iron Curtain.
World War I was a catalyst for this reversal, and during the two world wars and one global cold war, economic globalization saw a decline while military globalization increased.
This reflects deeper issues of domestic inequality caused by economic development in the 19th century.
Politics failed to adapt to economic development, resulting in abnormal ideologies—fascism and communism reaching their peak—fueling a pathological development that fragmented both nations and the world.
Post-World War II welfare states in the West provided a safety net for those harmed by economic changes, encouraging them to embrace the benefits of economic interdependence in the global economy.
Some analysts believe that China's role today is similar to that of Germany in the 20th century.
They are rising forces troubled by domestic unevenness, constantly moving toward nationalism, challenging the dominant powers, ultimately leading to world wars that reverse the progress of economic globalization.
Although the economies of the United States and China are highly interdependent today, the economies of Britain and Germany were no less so before 1914.
But such reasoning is not entirely sound.
After 1900, Germany's industrial production had surpassed that of Britain.
But even maintaining its current high growth rate, China's economy is unlikely to catch up with that of the United States within at least two decades.
A greater threat to the flat world comes from the non-state and transnational forces unleashed by the spread of technology.
On September 11, 2001, a non-state network killed more Americans in a surprise attack than Japan's government did in Pearl Harbor in 1941.
I refer to this phenomenon as privatization of war.
If such forces obtained nuclear weapons and biological materials, the world would be turned upside down.
At that time, crossing borders for people and goods would become more difficult.
If such forces were to disrupt oil exports from the Persian Gulf, which accounts for two-thirds of the world's oil reserves, a global economic recession on the scale of the 1930s could further strengthen the power of protectionism.
Technology and policy are the two major drivers of globalization.
So far, policies have further reinforced the flattening effect of technology.
As the world's largest economic entity, the United States has taken the lead in promoting policies to eliminate barriers.
But the events described above might reverse this trend in policy.
Some critics of globalization might be willing to see such a result.
But such a result, as we saw after 1914, would lead to the worst outcomes in two areas: the reversal of the economic globalization trend in spreading technology and power, while the negative consequences of military and ecological globalization, such as warfare, terrorism, climate change, and the spread of infectious diseases, further entrench themselves.
If that were the case, the flat world would become a desert.
